column168: DRIVER STOPPED AT 5201 SPRUCE ST. IN BELLAIRE, TX TO MAKE A PICKUP.  AT THIS TIME, 1630 CST, HE NOTED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE NOSE AREA OF THE TRAILER.  KNOWING THAT HE HAD ONE DRUM OF HAZMAT (CLASS 8) IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER, THE DRIVER MOVED HIS TRACTOR AND TRAILER TO A SAFE AREA WHERE THE LEAKAGE WOULD DRIP ONTO SAND COVERED CONCRETE.  THE DRIVER BUILT UP A SAND BERM TO FURTHER CONTAIN THE SPILL.  HE REPORTED THE SPILL TO THE SAFETY DEPARTMENT.  THE SAFETY DEPARTMENT DISPATCHED THE COMPANY'S RESPONSE TEAM AND NOTIFIED THE CITY OF BELLAIRE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  A BELLAIRE F.D. UNIT ARRIVED FIRST AND SECURED THE SCENE.  WHEN THE UNDERSIGNED AND THE RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED, BELLAIRE F.D. PERSONNEL, USING SCBA PLACED THE LEAKER IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND APPLIED ABSORBANT MATERIAL TO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  SAND AND COMMERCIAL ABSORBENT WERE USED TO RECOVERY WHAT HAD SPILLED TO THE GROUND.  ALL ABSORBED MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN RECOVERY BAGS FOR LATER DISPOSAL. THE BELLAIRE F.D. PERSONNEL STOOD BY UNTIL RECOVERY WAS COMPLETE AT 1845.  THE TRAILER AND ABSORBED MATERIAL WERE RETURNED TO THE PALLETIZED TERMINAL AT 2001 COLLINGSWORTH IN HOUSTON. THE TRAILER WAS DECONTAMINATED AND AFTER CONSULTATION WITH THE APPROPRIATE FEDERAL AND STATE AGENCIES, THE ABSORBED MATERIAL WAS RECLASSIFIED AND RECYCLED AS A FERTILIZER.  THE RECOVERY DRUM CONTAINING THE LEAKER WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSAL OF ITS CONTENTS AND DECONTAMINATION.

column168: KANE TRANSPORT WAS UNLOADING GASOLINE FROM A TANK TRAILER AT VIRGILS SERVICE STATION IN ROCHESTER WHEN GASOLINE BEGAN RUNNING OUT OF THE TANK MONITER ACCESS PIPE.  THE GASOLINE RAN DOWN VIRGILS PARKING LOT, BUT THE DRIVER OF THE TRANSPORT WAS ABLE TO STOP IT WITH FLOOR DRY BEFORE IT RAN ONTO THE STREET.  KANE TRANSPORT PERSONNEL ARRIVED AT THE LOCATION THE NEXT MORNING TO CLEAN UP THE CONTAMINATED FLOORY DRY - WHICH IS NOW AT KANE TRANSPORT'S FACILITY IN EAGAN, MN AWAITING DISPOSAL.  WE BELIEVE THE VENT PIPE WAS PLUGGED AT THE STATION WHICH CAUSED PRESSURE TO BUILD IN THE TANK - BREAKING THE MONITORING DEVICE & CREATING A PASSAGE FOR THE GAS TO FLOW FROM THE TANK.

column168: AS A CARRIER HAVING KNOWLEDGE OF THIS INCIDENT, CSX TRANSPORTATION HAD FILLED THIS REPORT.  IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT THIS OCCURRED ON THE CONSIGNEE'S PROPERTY WHILE THE TANK CAR WAS PRESUMABLY BEING OFFLOADED. THIS CAR WAS NOT IN TRANSPORTATION AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT.  CSXT TRAIN R54001 WAS PASSING THE D.D. WILLIAMSON PLANT IN LOUISVILLE, KENTUCKY AND HEARD A LOUD "EXPLOSION" AND REPORTED SEEING MATERIAL BEING BLOWN TOWARDS THE TRACKS.  INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT A TANK CAR, UTLX 67863, LOADED WITH AMMONIUM BISULFITE HAD DEVELOPED EXCESS INTERNAL PRESSURE AND HAD VENTED VIOLENTLY THROUGH THE MANWAY.  THE MANWAY COVER WAS TORN FROM THE CAR AND THROWN APPROXIMATELY 400 YARDS FROM THE CAR.  A RESIDUE OF MATERIAL RELEASED FROM THE CAR WAS SPREAD OVER A LARGE AREA.  SEVERAL HOMES IN THE IMMEDIATE VICINITY WERE EVACUATED BY THE LOCAL POLICE AS A PRECAUTION. PLANT PERSONNEL FROM D.D. WILLIAMSON WERE RESPONSIBLE FOR CLEANUP AND REMEDIATION OF THE SITE.

column168: OUR LOGEX DRIVER WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON 159 CHANGING TO US 98E WHEN HE NOTICED VAPOR AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  THE WEATHER WAS RATHER HUMID AND A LIGHT MISTY RAIN FALLING, WHICH MADE IT DIFFICULT TO RECOGNIZE THE VAPOR FROM THE ROADSPRAY.  THE DRIVER INVESTIGATED AND FOUND THAT THE BOTTOM FILL VALVE HAD VIBRATED OPEN AND WAS FROZEN OPEN, MAKING IT IMPOSSIBLE TO CLOSE.  A FIRE TRUCK WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE AND WATER WAS USED TO THAW THE VALVE, THE VALVE WAS THEN CLOSED AND THE DELIVERY COMPLETED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  THE TRAILER WAS THOROUGHLY INSPECTED UPON ITS RETURN TO THE TERMINAL AND THE VALVE WAS OPERATING NORMALLY.  OUR INVESTIGATION INDICATED THAT MOISTURE FOUND ITS WAY INTO THE BONNET AND SEAT, WHICH FROZE WHEN THE VALVE VIBRATED OPEN AND CRYOGENIC LIQUID CONTACTED THE VALVE.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY, 1145 HOURS, WEDNESDAY, MARCH 6, 1996, TANK CAR UTLX 803627 (LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS (PROPANE) AT CONRAIL SELKIRK, NY RAIL YARD DURING ROUTINE HUMPING OPERATIONS SUDDENLY EXPLODED.  TANK CAR UTLX 803627 WAS HUMPED DOWN INTO A TRACK HOLDING FOUR OTHER CARS, 1 LOADED HOPPER, 3 EMPTY BOX CARS.  PRELIMINARY INDICATION NOTES THAT THE CAR EXPLODED APPROXIMATELY 3 MINUTES FOLLOWING CAR BEING RELEASED AT THE HUMP. EMPLOYEES WORKING THE AREA REPORTED A LOUD EXPLOSION AND LARGE FIRE BALL. PERSONNEL WERE ORDERED TO RETREAT TO A SPECIFIED GATERING AREA, NO INJURIES REPORTED.  APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.  THE NATIONAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY BOARD, FEDERAL RAILWAY ADMINISTRATION, ASSOCATION OF AMERICAN RAILROAD, NEW YORK STATE DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORATION, UNION TANK CAR, CONRAIL, SUBURBAN PROPANE, CONDUCTING INVESTIGATION.  FINAL ANALYSIS OF WHY TANK CAR RUPTURED AND SPLIT IN HALF CATCHING ON FIRE IS CONTINGENT ON FINDINGS.  CAR BUILT IN 1977 BY RICHMOND TANK CAR AND WAS ONE OF 83 CARS (IN A SERIES OF 85 CARS) PURCHASED BY UNION TANK CAR.  CAR WAS ORIGINALLY A  105A300W EQUIPPED WITH 2 1/4 INCH URETHANE INSULATION, TC-128 B STEEL.  CAR CONVERTED TO A 105J300W IN EARLY 1988.  EXISTING JACKET AND INSULATION REMOVED AND NEW MINERAL WOOL THERMAL PROTECTION, FIBERGLASS INSULATION, FULL HEAD SHIELDS AND NEW JACKET APPLIED.  NOTED DURING INVESTIGATION TANK CAR HAD NUMEROUS (10+) LOCATIONS WERE A WELD OVERLY (CLADDING) HAD BEEN APPLIED TO BUILD UP THINNED BASE METAL, THIS APPARENTLY DUE TO PITTING CAUSED BY MOISTURE BUILD UP BETWEEN URETHANE INSULATION AND SHELL.  CAR SPLIT JUST ON THE A END SIDE OF THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING.  THE TEAR DIDN'T FOLLOW A WELD SEAM.  THE NTSB METALLURGIST ON SCENE SUSPECTS THAT THE CAR FIRST SPLIT AT THE TOP OF THE CAR, PERHAPS JUST AN INCH OR TWO TO THE LEFT OF THE LONGITUDINAL CENTER.  IT WAS NOTED THAT THIS IS ALSO THE CORNER LOCATION OF WHERE ONE OF THE WELD OVERLAYS HAD BEEN APPLIED.  IT IS SUSPECTED AND TESTS TO BE CONDUCTED IN WASHINGTON TO CONFIRM A CONNECTION BETWEEN THE ORIGIN OF THE CRACK, THE WELD OVERLAY AND THE PROXIMITY TO THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING FLANGE ARE THE CAUSE OF THE A END TANK CAR FAILURE.

TANK CAR WAS REPORTED LEAKING FROM THE TOP WHILE SITTING STILL AT CSXT'S RAIL YARD IN JACKSONVILE, FL. THE MANWAY GASKET ALSO APPEARED TO THE WORN.  THE CAR WAS SECURED AND RELEASED AT 1830 HRS.

column168: A VACUUM TRAILER WAS DISPATCHED TO POLAROID CORP. LOCATED AT 1 UPLAND ROAD IN NORWOOD, MA IN ORDER TO LOAD A CHROMIUM BEARING WASTE FOR OFF-SIRE DISPOSAL.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, THE DRIVER INITIATED STEPS TO BEGIN THE LOADING PROCEDURE AND INITIATE PUMPING MATERIAL FROM 55 GALLON DRUMS NOTICED THAT THE PUMPING ACTION OF THE PRODUCT CREATED A LAYER OF FOAM IN THE VACUUM TANK WHICH PASSED THROUGH BOTH THE PRIMARY AND SECONDARY SHUTOFF VALVE INTO THE EXHAUST STACK OF THE SCRUBBER UNIT.  THE FOAM WAS THEN RELEASED THROUGH THE EXHAUST STACK ONTO THE ASPHALT LOADING AREA.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE LOADING OPERATIONS CONTACTED BOTH THE ON-SITE CONTACT AND HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR.  FACILITY PERSONNEL CONTAINED THE RELEASE AND ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUID WITH AN APPROPRIATE ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS WAS CONTAINERIZED AND PLACED INTO STORAGE PENDING OFF-SITE DISPOSAL.  PLEASE NOTE THAT PURSUANT TO THE REQUIREMENTS OF CLEAN HARBOR'S MASSACHUSETTS ISSUED HAZARDOUS WASTE TRANSPORTATION PERMIT.  THIS INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO A MR. BRAD STEWART OF THE MASSACHUSETTS DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AND WAS NOTED AS A NON REPORTABLE RELEASE UNDER EXISTING MASSACHUSETTS REQUIREMENTS.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE, THE DRIVER HAS BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO REDUCE THE VACUUM PRESSURE ON THE PUMPING SYSTEM WHEN LOADING MATERIALS WHICH HAVE THE POTENTIAL TO FORMA A FOAM LAYER CAUSED BY THE LOADING PROCEDURES.

A VACUUM TRAILER WAS DISPATCHED TO GROVE STREET IN NATIONAL PARK, NJ IN ORDER TO LOAD AND TRANSPORT A SHIPMENT OF NON REGULATED RAINWATER FOR DISPOSAL.  PRIOR TO DISPATCH, THE DRIVER PERFORMED THE REQUIRED PRE-TRIP INSPECTION OF THE VEHICLE HE WAS ASSIGNED TO OPERATE.  THIS INCLUDED AN INSPECTION OF THE VEHICLE'S SCRUBBER SYSTEM WHICH IS CONDUCTED IN ORDER TO ENSURE THAT THERE IS NO RESIDUAL MATERIAL IN THIS UNIT FROM A PREVIOUS SHIPMENT.  THE DRIVER FOUND ON RESIDUAL MATERIAL IN THIS SYSTEM DURING THE PRETRIAL INSPECTION.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE GROVE STREET LOCATION, THE DRIVER INITIATED THE LOADING PROCDURE AND PROCEEDED TO LOAD APPROXIMATELY 4000 GALLONS.  AT THIS POINT, THE DRIVER STOPPED THE LOADING OPERATIONS IN ORDER TO CONFIRM THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT ON THE VEHICLE BY CONDUCTING A VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE REMAINING CAPACITY IN THE TANK.  IN ORDER TO STOP THE LOADING OPERATIONS, THE PUMP SYSTEM WAS STOPPED AND THE VACUUM/PRESSURE VALVE WAS PLACED INTO THE NEUTRAL POSITION TO RELIEVE THE VACUUM PRESSURE ON THE TANK.  THE DRIVER CONFIRMED THAT AN ADDITIONAL 1000 GALLONS COULD BE LOADED INTO THE VEHICLE AND INITIATED THE PUMPING OPERATIONS.  THE REMAINING 1000 GALLONS WAS LOADED AND THE DRIVER BEGAN CLEARING THE TRANSFER HOSED OF ANY REMAINING PRODUCT.  IT WAS AT THIS TIME THAT THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE SCRUBBER UNIT OF THE VEHICLE ONTO THE GROUND.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE PUMP MECHANISM AND CONTACTED BOTH THE ON-SITE CONTACT AND HIS DISPATCHER FOR ASSISTANCE.  A CLEAN-UP CREW WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SITE TO ASSIST IN THE CLEAN-UP OPERATIONS.  UPON ARRIVAL, THE CREW CONTAINED THE RELEASE, CONTAINERIZED 3 X 55 GALLON CONTAINER OF CONTAMINATED SOIL AND 1 X 55 GALLON DRUM OF CONTAMINATED RAINWATER.  THIS MATERIAL WAS PREPARED FOR OFF-SITE SHIPMENT AND SENT TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, IN. LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVENUE IN BRAINTREE, MA.  PLEASE NOTE THAT PURSUANT TO THE REQUIREMENTS OF CLEAN HARBORS'S NEW JERSEY ISSUED HAZARDOUS SOILED WASTE TRANSPORTERS PERMITS, THIS INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE NEW JERSEY DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTIONS ("NJDEP") AND WAS ASSIGNED CASE # 96-3-15-1318-39.  PSE & G (PROPERTY OWNER) ALSO REPORTED THIS RELEASE TO THE NJDEP AND WAS ISSUED CASE NUMBER 96-3-15-1142-34.  TH PSE & G CONTACT JOHN HALPIN (609-599-7134).  BOTH CASE NUMBER IDENTIFIED ABOVE REPRESENT THE SAME INCIDENT.  IN ADDITION, THE SITE WAS VISITED BY REPRESENTATIVE OF BOTH THE NATIONAL PARK POLICE DEPARTMENT AND THE BOROUGH EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT COORDINATOR.  THE DRIVER THEN DELIVERED THE LOAD TO THE INTENDED RECEIVING FACILITY WHERE THE VEHCILE WAS OFF LOADED.  THE DRIVER THEN PROCEEDED TO CLEAN HARBOR'S  DEPTFORD SERVICE CENTER WHERE A COMPANY MECHANIC DEISCOVERED THAT MATERIAL FROM A PREVIOUS SHIPMENT HAD SOLIDIFIED IN THE EXHAUST LINE OF THE SCRUBBER SYSTEM PREVENTING RESIDUAL MATERIAL FROM REACHING THE COLLECTION AREA OF THIS SYSTEM THAT IS ROUTINELY CHECKED DURING THE PRE-TRIP

A VACUUM TRAILER WAS DISPATHED TO GENERAL ELECTRIC COMPANY LOCATED AT 1 NORYL AVENUE IN SELKIRK, NY IN ORDER TO TRANSPORT A SHIPMENT OF HAZARDOUS WASTE TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CLEVELAND, INC.  LOCATED AT 2900 BROADWAY IN CLEVELAND, OH.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, THE DRIVER POSITIONED THE VEHICLE AT THE LOADING AREA AND WAS INSTRUCTED TO WAIT IN THE DRIVER'S BREAK ROOM WHILE THE MATERIAL WAS LOADED ONTO HIS VEHICLE. DURING THE LOADING PROCEDURE, AN EMPLOYEE OF GENERAL ELECTRIC WHO WAS ASSISTING WITH THE LOADING INSPECTED THE PROGRESSION OF THE LOADING OPERATIONS BY LOOKING INTO THE TANK THROUGH THE TOP DOME HATCH WHICH WAS OPEN.  AS HE LOOKED INTO THE TANK, A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL SPLASHED OUT OF THE TRANSFER HOSE ONTO THIS INDIVIDUAL.  THE LOADING OPERATION WAS IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN AND THE INDIVIDUAL RINSED HIMSELF OFF UNDER AN EMERGENCY EYEWASH/SHOWER STATION AND REMOVED ALL CONTAMINATED CLOTHING . THERE WERE NO INNJURIED AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT NOR WAS THERE ANY CLEAN-UP DEBRIS GENERATED DUE TO THE SMALL ANMOUNT OF MATERIAL RELEASED. ONCE FACILITY PERSONNEL WERE SATISIFIED THAT THE INDIVIDUAL CONTAMINATED WAS NOT INJURED, LOADING ACTIVITIES RESUMED.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE, LOADING PERSONNEL HAVE RECEIVED A REVISED LOADING PROCEDURE THAT WILL BE FOLLOWED ON ALL FUTURE LOADING OPERATIONS.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1615 HOURS 3/21/96 HOURS 3/21/96, A UNION PACICIF SWITCH CREW OBSERVED PRODUCT COMING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS. UNION PACIFIC SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIAL KEN DECHANT INSPECTED CAR SOME DATE, NOTING THAT THE FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY HAD FAILED.  DECHANT REPLACED THE DISC WITH AN IDENTICAL BS&B STAINLESS STEEL TEFLON 100# DISC. ALL OTHER FITTING FOUND TO BE SECURE.  NO SPILLAGE NOTED ON THE SIDES OF THE CAR OR ON THE GROUND. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSED AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT.  SHIPPER WAS FURNISHED DETAILS OF RELEASE.  INCIDNET IS EXEMPTED FROM IOWA STATE REPORTING REQUIREMENTS.

column168: A VACUUM TRAILER WAS DISPATCHED TO CUSTOM CAPTIVE LOCATED AT 100 PENCATER AVENUE IN NEWARK, DE IN ORDER TO LOAD AND TRANSPORT A SHIPMENT OF HAZARDOUS WASTE FOR OFF-SITE DISPOSAL.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE LOADING SITE, THE DRIVER INITIATED THE STEPS NECESSARY TO BEGIN THE LOADING PROCEDURES. ONE STEP IN THIS PROCEDURE INVOLVES THE OPENING OF THE DRAIN VALVES OF THE VEHICLE'S SCRUBBER SYSTEM AND VACUUM PUMP ASSEMBLY IN ORDER TO DRAIN ANY RESIDUAL LIQUID THAT COULD HAVE COLLECTED IN THESE SYSTEMS FROM A PREVIOUS SHIPMENT.  THE DRIVER PERFORMED THIS STEP AND CLOSED THE DRAIN VALVE AFTER IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE SYSTEMS CONTAINED NO RESIDUAL LIQUID.  ONCE THE SETUP AND INSPECTION OF THE VEHICLE WAS COMPLETE, THE DRIVER ENGAGED THE VACUUM PUMP IN ORDER TO INITIATE THE LOADING OF PRODUCT INTO THE TANK.  IT WAS AT THIS POINT THAT APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT OF MATERIAL ESCAPED FROM THE EXHAUST STACK OF THE SCRUBBER SYSTEM ONTO THE ASPHALT CONTAINMENT LOADING AREA.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE OPERATION AND NOTIFIED BOTH THE MANAGEMENT OF CUSTOM CAPTIVE AND HIS HOME DISPATCHER OF THE INCIDENT. A CLEAN UP CREW WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE AND UPON ARRIVAL, PROCEEDED TO ABSORB ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SUITABLE ABSORBENT PADS.  THIS MATERIAL WAS CONTAINERIZED AND SENT FOR DISPOSAL TO A LICENSED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY.  A REVIEW OF THE INCIDENT INDICATED THAT THE PROBABLE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE CAN BE ATTRIBUTED TO MATERIAL FROM A PREVIOUS LOAD FREEZING IN THE EXHAUST STACK OF THE SCRUBBER SYSTEM.  IT IS BELIEVED THAT THE PRESSURE CREATED WHEN THE VACUUM UNIT WAS TURNED ON DISLODGED AN ICE PLUG ALLOWING RESIDUAL LIQUID BEHIND THE ICE PLUG TO ESCAPE FROM THE EXHAUST STACK.  PLEASE NOTE THAT THE FORMATION OF AN ICE PLUG PREVENTED THE DRIVER FROM DISCOVERING THE PRESENCE OF RESIDUAL LIQUID IN THESE SYSTEMS DURING HIS INITIAL INSPECTION.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE, THE DRIVER HAS BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO ENSURE THAT ALL SCRUBBER UNITS ARE DRAINED COMPLETELY PRIOR TO SUBSEQUENT DISPATCH.

ON 3/27/96 AT 0800 TRAIN 01251 DERAILED THE 37 THROUGH 48 HEAD CARS, SEVEN OF THESE CARS CONTAINED DENATURED ALCOHOL, 3, NA1986.  TANK CAR NATX29696 SUSTAINED A PUNCTURE NEAR THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAUSING THE CAR TO EMPTY.  THE RELEASED PRODUCT STARTED A FIRE.  THE FIRE CAUSED THE DENATURED ALCOHOL IN TANK CAR GATX79847 TO HEAT UP, WHICH INCREASED THE TANK CAR'S INTERNAL PRESSURE.  THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVES COULD NOT RELEASE THE PRESSURE FAST ENOUGH AND THE CAR RUPTURED IN THE VAPOR SPACE NEAR THE END OF THE CAR.  THE FIRE WAS EXTINGUISHED AND THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED TO HIGHWAY TRANSPORTS.  IT IS BELIEVED THAT MOST OF THE 30,000 GALLONS OF PRODUCT LOST WAS CONSUMED IN THE FIRE. UPON ARRIVAL OF A INBOUND OKC TRUCK AT 1800 WEDNESDAY, MARCH 27, 1996; A PALLET OF 3 PERC DRUMS (POLY) WERE NOT PROPERLY SECURED TO THE PALLET FOR TRAVEL AND THEY SHIFTED AND SPILLED DURING TRANSPORT.  APPROXIMATELY 6-7 GALLONS OF MATERIAL SPILLED.  THESE DRUMS SHOULD BE SHRINK WRAPPED AND SECURED WITH STRAPS TO THE TRAILER BEFORE BEING TRANSPORTED.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS TETRACHLOROETHYLENE (PERC). THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN THE TRUCK (AS SHOWN IN THE PICTURES) TWO PEOPLE (TOMMY HERZFELD & STEVE BAUGUS) WERE INVOLVED IN THE SPILL CLEAN-UP.

THE FAULTY CARTON WAS PLACED IN A PLASTIC HAZARDOUS MATERIAL BAG AND PLACED IN OS & D AWAITING DISPOSITION.

WHILE UNLOADING, DOCK PERSON PUNCTURED ONE CARTON CONTAINING 4 PAILS WITH A FORKLIFT BLADE.  THE PRODUCT WAS ISOLATED RIGHT AWAY AND PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM.  EMPLOYEE PLACED OIL DRY IN BOTTOM OF DRUM AND BOTTOM OF PLASTIC BAG AND PLACED IN PLASTIC BAG AND SEALED SALVAGE DRUM.

DRUMS THAT HAD BEEN BILLED AS EMPTY LAST CONTAINED WERE DISCOVERED TO HAVE LEAKED THE REMAINDER OF LIQUID WHILE IN TRANSIT.  THERE WERE REMOVED FROM TRAILER AND PLACED IN OS & D FOR RECOOPING AND REQUIREMENTS.

USING DRUM DOLLY TO PICK UP DRUM AND RECEIVEING PERSON SAID DRUM WAS LEAKING.  THERE WAS DRIED PAINT UNDER DRUM WHEN IT WAS MOVED.  DRUM LEAKED AGAIN AND THEN WE PUT ONTO DUNNAGE UNTIL TRAILER WAS UNLOADED.  ALSO, WE WERE GOING TO CHECK IF CONSIGNEE WOULD RECEIVED AND PUT IN THEIR OWN RECOVERY DRUM BUT THEY WOULD NOT.  VERY LITTLE RESIN SOLUTION IN TRAILER. THERE WAS NO NAIL UNDER THE DRUM SO IT IS UNKNOWN WHAT CAUSED THE LEAK.

column168: INCIDENT OCCURED AT AUGLAIZE FAMERS IN WAPAKONETA, OHIO.  THE DRIVER OVERFILLED A 4000 GALLON TANK WHICH ALREADY CONTAINED 2860 GALLON OF PRODUCT. SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE (OCCIDENTAL CHEMICAL) RESPONDED AT 1815 HOURS, MARCH 26, 1996 AND INSPECTED THE RAIL CAR.  RAIL CAR SECURED FOR SHIPPER INVESTIGATION.  SHIPPERS REPRESENTATIVE (OCCIDENTAL CHEMICAL) INSPECTED RAIL CAR, REPLACING DEFECTIVE DOME COVER GASKET AND ORDERED THE CAR RETURNED TO THE PLANT FACILITY AT NIAGARA FALLS, NY. THE CUSTOMER ORDERED 18,360 LBS OF SULFIURIC ACID 66' BE'.  THE DRIVER DELIVERED 17,840 LBS. AND THE TANK OVERFLOWED. THERE WERE NO GAUGES ON THE TANK AND THE TANK WAS COMPLETELY FULL.  THE DRIVER WAS NOTIFIED BY THE CUSTOMER'S EMPLOYEE THAT THE TANK HAD OVERFLOWED.  THE CELAN UP WAS DONE BY SPENCER ENVIRONMENTAL AND IS DUE TO BE SHIPPER OUT THIS WEEK TO PHILIP ENVIRONMENTAL.  SINCE THE WASTE HAD NOT SHIPPED OUT YET, WE DO NOT HAVE A COPY OF THE MANIFEST.  THERE WILL BE TWO PERSONS REQUIRED FOR EACH OFF-LOAD AT THIS FACILITY IN THE FUTURE.  ONE TO WATCH THE TRUCK HOOK UPS AND ONE TO WATCH THE TANK.  THIS SECOND PERSON WILL BE SUPPLIED BY THE CUSTOMER. ALSO THE CUSTOMER MUST ENSURE THAT THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT ORDERED WILL FIT INTO THEIR TANK.

A ROLL-OFF CONTAINER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS PREPARED FOR SHIPMENT AT SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY INC. LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVENEU IN CINCINNATI, OH DESTINED FOR CWM CHEMICAL SERVICES INC. LOCATED AT 1550 BALMER ROAD IN MODEL CITY, NY.  ONCE THE CONTAINER WAS LOADED, IT WAS PLACED INTO STORAGE PENDING AUTHORIZATION TO SHIP TO A THIRD PART WASTE DISPOSAL FACILITY.  UPON CONFIMATION OF THE DISPOSAL AUTHORIZATION, THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE PREPARED IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED ONTO AN ASPHALT PARKING AREA.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE AND NOTIFIED FACILITY PERSONNEL OF INCIDENT.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY RESPONDED AND ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUID THAT WAS NOT PRESENT AT THE TIME THE CONTAINER WAS LOADED COLLECTED AT THE REAR DOOR AND ESCAPED THROUGH A GAP BETWEEN THE DOOR AND THE RUBBER GASKET USED TO CREATE A SEAL WHEN THE DOOR IS SHUT.  IT APPEARS THAT THE GASKET WAS "PINCHED" ALLOWING A PROPER SEAL NOT TO BE ACHIEVED.  FACILITY PERSONNEL FIXED THE GASKET AND SOLIDIFIED ALL FREE LIQUIDS PRIOR TO THE SHIPMENT CONTINUING TO THE INTENDED DESTINATION.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE, LOADING PERSONNEL HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO ENSURE THAT ALL GASKET ARE SEATED PROPERLY WHEN THE DOORS ARE CLOSED.  IN ADDITION, ADDITIONAL ABSORBENT MATERIAL IS TO BE PLACED AT THE BACK DOORS OF ROLL-OFFS TO ABSORB ANY FREE LIQUIDS WHICH MIGHT PHASE OUT OF THE SOLID LOAD DURING TRANSPORTATION.

column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, LOW SPECIFIC ACTIVITY (LSA-I) NON FISSILE OR FISSILE-EXCEPTED
column168: THE WYOMING HIGHWAY PATROL WAS NOTIFIED OF A SPILL INVOLVING A RADIOLOGICAL MATERIAL AT 1311 HOURS ON MARCH 31, 1996.  WYOMING EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY RECEIVED A CALL AT 1330 HOURS NOTIFYING A SPILL, AND IN TURN CONTACTED THE SHIPPER AND THE CARRIER.  THE SHIPPER REQUESTED STATE RESPONSE TEAM BE PUT ON STANDBY.  THE TEAM CHECKED IN BY 1430 HOURS.  WE DECIDED NOT TO ACTIVATE THE ENTIRE TEAM BASED ON THE ASSESSMENT FROM HIGHWAY PATROL ON THE SCENE.  INSTEAD WE DECIDED TO RESPOND WITH TWO PERSONNEL TO ARRIVED IN LARAMIE THE SAME TIME AS THE CLEANUP TEAM FROM THE SHIPPER.  THEY ARRIVED AT 1900 HOURS AT PETRO TRUCK STOP.  THERE WAS TWO AIR/SEA CONTAINERS ON A FLATBED SEMI-TRAILER.  CONTAINER #1, ON THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER, HAD A TOTAL LOAD WEIGHT OF 9,095 LBS.  TOTAL AMOUNT OF RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL WAS 0.594 MCI.  CONTAINER #2, DIRECTLY IN BACK OF CONTAINER #1, HAD A LOAD WEIGHT OF 7.730 LBS.  TOTAL AMOUNT OF RADIOLOGICAL MATERIAL WAS 0.505 MCI.  THE LOAD ITSELF CONTAINED ONLY TRACE AMOUNTS OF U-238; TC-99; NP-237, PU-239.  WE WERE UNABLE TO DETECT ANY RADIATION COMING FROM THE OIL LEAKING OUT OF THE TRAILER OR ANYWHERE ELSE. WE ALSO DETERMINED THE LEAK IN THE TRAILER WAS COMING FROM THE SECOND CONTAINER IN THE MIDDLE OF THE RIGHT SIDE.  TWO OF THEIR TEAM MEMBERS SUITED UP.  THEY USED SUITS, BOOTS, AND GLOVES WITH NO BREATHING EQUIPMENT OR HOODS.  THE LOCKHEED TEAM TOOK SEVERAL  SWIPES IN SEVERAL DIFFERENT LOCATIONS AND PUT THEM TO A METER AND WERE UNABLE TO DETECT ANY RADIATION. THEY USED ABSORBENT PADS AND AN OIL ABSORBENT TO CLEAN UP.  ONCE THE OUTSIDE OF THE TRAILER AND THE GROUND WAS CLEANED, THEY  PREPARED THE AREA SO THEYCOULD OPEN THE CONTAINER. THE SEAL ON THE CONTAINER WAS BROKEN AT2054 HOURS.  THE RIGHT CONTAINER DOOR WAS OPENED TO DISCOVER NUMEROUS YELLOW RADIOLOGICCAL  BAGS FILLED WITH  WASTE.  THE TEAM STARTED GOING THROUGH THE BAGS AND FOUND TWO THAT WERE RIPPED OPEN AND CONTAINED OIL. THEY REBAGGED THEM AND ADDED MORE ABSORBING MATERIALTO THE NEW BAG.  THE ORIGINAL LOADING OF THE MATERIAL WAS IMPROPER, BECAUSE THERE WAS NOT ENOUGH ABSORBING MATERIAL IN SEVERAL OF THEM.  CONSEQUENTLY, YOU COULD SEE STANDING LIQUID IN THEM.  ALL OF THOSE BAGS WERE REPACKAGED.   ONCE THEY HAD THE SCENE CLEANED UP,  WE CHECKED THEIR WORK  AND FOUND THEY DID AN ACCEPTABLE JOB IN CLEANING UP THE SPILL.  THE SCENE WAS CLEARED AT APPROXIMATELY 2223 HOURS.  NEXT WE BRIEFED THE TRUCK STOP MANAGEMENT TEAM AT 2333, AND WE DEPARTED FOR CHEYENNE.  WE ARRIVED AT 2400 HOURS. DEATHS AND INJURIES:  NONE REPORTED.  POTENTIAL THREAT: DAMAGE TO PETRO, INC. PROPERTY AND POSSIBLE CONTAMINATTION TO PUBLIC.  WEMA ASSESSMENT:  A. CAUSE OF SPILL WAS IMPROPER PACKAGING OF THE LSA MATERIAL BY LOCKHEED MARTIN UTILITY SERVICES, INC. IN PADUCAH, KY.  B.  JAMES M. MORGAN OF RANGER LANDSTAR TRUCKING COMPANY NEEDS TO BE COMMENDED FOR DISCOVERING THE LEAK AND CALLING HIS EMPLOYER.  C.  LOCKHEED MARTIN UTILITY SERVICES'S CLEAN-UP TEAM, AND THEIR TEAM LEADER, PHILIP G. BROWN, PERFORME

I FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE AND FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEETS.  I USED SOLUSORB TO ABSORB AND PROCESSED IN DMP SYSTEM.  THE REMAINING BOTTLE WAS SENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.  I USED SCBA, AND KAMY PARKS WAS MY BACKUP RESPONDER.

column168: THE FOLLOWING IS THE SEQUENCE OF EVENTS LEADING TO THE COAL TAR PITCH RELEASE FROM A LEASED KOPPERS INDUSTRIES, INC. (KII) TANK CAR ON MARCH 8, 1996.  TRANSIT TANK IS THE OWNER OF THE TANK CAR.  TANK CAR UTLX 650836 WAS HAVING A PROBLEM COMING UP TO TEMPERATURE IN ORDER TO HEAT THE SOLIDIFIED COAL TAR PITCH SUFFICIENTLY FOR UNLOADING.  ON MARCH 6, 1996 A SERVICE CALL WAS MADE TO KII.  THEIR CONTRACTOR, SCHMIDT ELECTRIC, ARRIVED TO WORK ON THE PROBLEM ON MARCH 8, 1996.  THE SCHMIDT ELECTRIC SERVICE PERSON DETERMINED THAT THERE MIGHT BE A PROBLEM WITH ONE OF THE TWO THERMCOUPLES.  TO TEST THIS THEORY HE ATTEMPTED TO REPLACE THE THERMCOUPLE WITH ANOTHER ONE.  HE ENCOUNTERED PROBLEMS INSERTING THE TEST THERMCOUPLE INTO THE WELL HOUSING AND BELIEVED THAT THE OBSTRUCTION WAS ON THE REDUCING NUT OR IN THE WELL ITSELF.  HE BELIEVED THAT THE WELL WOULD BE WELDED INTO PLACE AND THAT IT WOULD BE AN INTRICATE PART OF THE TANKER CAR.  IN NEWER CARS THIS IS THE CASE.  THERE WERE NO WARNINGS ON THE RAIL CAR INDICATING THAT THE THERMOWELL WAS REMOVABLE AND COULD RESULT IN DIRECT CONTACT WITH THE CONTENTS OF THE TANK CAR.  THE SERVICEMAN REMOVED WHAT HE BELIEVED TO BE A REDUCING NUT OR BUSHING AND COAL TAR PITCH SHOT OUT OF THE ONE INCH OPENING.  THE LEAK STOPPED BY FORCING A WOODEN POLE INTO THE HOLE AN APPLYING WATER TO THE STOPPER TO HELP SOLIDIFIED THE PITCH.  THE SPILLED PITCH WAS DIKED AND CONTAINED IN A PIT.  APPROXIMATE LOSS OF COAL TAR PITCH WAS 10 PERCENT THE TANK CAR HAS A CAPACITY OF 19,287 GALLONS.

ON MARCH 12, 1996 AN OIL DELIVERY WAS MADE TO 1705 ARLINGTON AVE., BALTIMORE, MD.  THE OFFICE WAS NOTIFIED OF THE OIL TANK FALLING OVER AT APPROXIMATELY 07:45 AM, MARCH 13, 1996, WHEN THE OFFICE OPENED FOR BUSINESS.   THE SECRETARY THEN CALLED MR. MANNONE WHO AT THAT TIME TOLD HER THAT THE TANK HAD FALLEN, ONE OF THE LEGS HAD BROKEN OFF.  A DISPATCH WAS MADE AND GIVEN TO THE SERVICE DEPARTMENT TO ACT ON.  ANDY RESPONDED AT 8:15AM TO START CLEANUP PROCEDURES.  A LEG ON THE OIL TANK WAS RUSTED PART WAY THROUGH AND IN COMBINATION WITH THE SOFT GROUND, CAUSED THE TANK TO FALL OVER.  THE HOMEOWNER HAD PROPPED THE TANK UP ON A 45 DEGREE ANGLE WITH BOARDS AND BLOCKS, AND I SHUT OFF THE VALVE AT THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK.  I THEN RETURNED, I PUT DOWN FUEL ABSORBENT AND REPLACED THE FUEL TANK.  AT THIS TIME THE STATE AND FEDERAL WERE NOTIFIED.  THE HOMEOWNER ID DOING HIS OWN CLEANUP.

THE BOX CONTAINS "HAWKER ENERGY CYCLON, SEALED-LEAD RECHARGEABLE BATTERY'S".  SEVERAL OF THE BATTERY'S WERE LOOSE ON THE SORT SLIDE, THE BATTERY TERMINALS CONNECTED WITH EACH OTHER. THE REMAINING PIECES WERE LOCATED AND THE LOOSE BATTERY'S WERE REPACKED.  THE BOX RESEALED AND TAKEN TO THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE.  THIS SHIPMENT WILL REMAIN UNDER LOCK AND KEY UNTIL FAA INVESTIGATION HAS BEEN COMPLETED.  EACH BOX HAS 2 LAYERS OF 50 BATTERY'S EACH.  TOTAL 100 BATTERY'S PER BOX.  TOTAL NUMBER OF BATTERY'S IN THIS SHIPMENT:  1000. INNER PACKAGING CONSISTS OF BATTERY'S SEGREGATED BY CARDBOARD DIVIDERS WITH A LAYER OF STYROFOAM  SHEETING ACROSS THE TOP.  BOTH LAYERS ARE PACKED IN THE SAME MANNER.   ALL TEN BOXES ARE PACKED IN THE SAME MANNER. CAUSE OF THE BOX TO OPEN AND THE BATTERY'S TO SPILL OUT.  THE PACKAGING TAPE ON THE OUTER BOX FAILED.  NONE OF THE BATTERY'S WERE DAMAGED OR LOST ANY OF THE LEAD SEALED INSIDE.  SOME OF THE BATTERY'S ARE CHARRED AT THE TERMINALS.  A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED FROM THE SHIPPER TO DETERMINE IF THESE BATTERY'S ARE CLASSIFIED AS A REGULATED MATERIAL.  MSDS HAS BEEN RECEIVED, AND IT INDICATES THE BATTERY'S ARE NOT REGULATED BY THE DOT OR ICAD.  A COPY OF THE MSDS WILL BE ATTACHED TO THIS REPORT ALONG WITH A COPY OF THE DOT 5800 FORM.  THIS SHIPMENT HAS BEEN REPACKED IN A RECOVERY DRUM FOR TRANSPORT TO PREVENT ACCIDENTAL ARCHING.

column168: 03-05-96, SORT LEAD BARRY COCCRAN REPORTED A LEAKING SHIPMENT IN PRIMARY OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON OHIO.  TIME REPORTED TO HAZ MAT DISPATCH: 01:40.  HAZ MAT COORDINATOR FRAN VANCE AND P\T HAZ MAT SPILL TECHNICIAN KEN HAAG RESPONDED TO THE SPILL. UPON ARRIVAL WE FOUND A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX WITH AN OILY TYPE SUBSTANCE ON THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX.  WE OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND 4-7FL OZ METAL CANS OF CITRUS 11 AIR FRESHNER HAD LEAKED APPROX 4 OUNCES.  NONE OF THE BOXES OF ALCOHOL PREP PADS HAD LEAKED.  WE RESEALED THE BOX, PLACED IT IN 2 PLASTIC BAGS AND HELD THE SHIPMENT FOR FAA INVESTIGATION DUE TO THE CANS OF AIR FRESHNER CONTENTS BEING UNDER PRESSURE.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INSIDE THE SECURITY CAGE IN THE HAZ MAT AREA, UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.  THERE ARE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ATTACHED TO THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THIS SHIPMENT IS A REGULATED MATERIAL. CAUSE OF THE LEAKAGE IS DUE TO THE SNAP ON CAPS WERE NOT SECURE ON 3 OF THE FOUR METAL CANS.  EACH CAN IS EQUIPPED WITH A PUSH TYPE SPRAY NOZZLE.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION OF THE CONTENTS, THE FOLLOWING INFORMATION WAS OBTAINED FROM THE CANS.  FRONT: CITRUS 11 ALL NATURAL PURE CITRUS AIR FRAGRANCE, NON AEROSOL.  BACK:  100% PURE SPECIALLY FORMULATED CITRUS FRAGRANCE OILS FROM LEMONS, ORANGES, LIMES, TANGERINES AND GRAPEFRUIT.  UNIQUE SPRAY CONTAINER, CITRUS 11 IS SEALED IN AN INTERIOR POUCH WHICH IS SURROUNDED AND PRESURIZED WITH NITROGEN.  WHEN SPRAYING, ONLY 100% PURE CITRUS 11 IS EXPELLED INTO THE AIR.  PRECAUTION:  CONTENTS UNDER PRESSURE.  DO NOT PUNCTURE OR INCINERATE.  DO NOT EXPOSE TO TEMPERATURE ABOVE 125 DEGREES F.  FLAMMABLE:  DO NOT USE NEAR FIRE OR FLAME.  KEEP OUT OF REACH OF CHILDERN.  A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET HAS BEEN REQUESTED FROM THE SHIPPER, AND WILL BE ATTACHED TO THIS REPORT UPON RECEIPT.

O3/20/96 AT 04:20 HAZ COORDINATOR FRAN VANCE UNLOADED A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX THAT WAS SHOWING VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE. column168: A VACUUM TRAILER WAS DISPATCHED TO BICRAFT INDUSTRIES, INC.  LOCATED AT 12 INDUSTRIAL AVENUE IN WALDWICK, NJ IN ORDER TO LOAD AND TRANSPORT A SHIPMENT OF WASTE MATERIAL TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE, INC. LOCATED AT 1910 RUSSELL STREET IN BALTIMORE MD.  DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER MADE A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBOR'S DEPTFORD SERVICE CENTER LOCATED AT 2301 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE IN DEPTFORD, NJ.  AT THIS LOCATIONS, THE DRIVER IDENTIFIED A MINOR DRIP COMING FROM THE BOTTOM VALVE OF THE TANK VEHICLE.  THE DRIVER IMMEIDATELY PLACED A CONTANIMENT BUCKER UNDER THE VALVE AND NOTIFIED BOTH HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR AND THE ON-SITE MECHANIC.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT IN ORDER TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK AND AFFECT REPAIRS, THE VEHICLE WOULD NEED TO BE UNLOADED.  A CALL WAS THEN PLACED TO THE STATE OF NJ TO SECURE PERMISSION TO CONDUCT A TRUCK TO TRUCK TRANSFER OF HAZARDOUS WASTE.  PERMISSION WAS OBTAINED (CASE #96-3-25-1544-32) AND A SECOND VEHICLE WAS DISPATCHED TO RECEIVE THE SHIPMENT.  UPON ARRIVAL OF THE SECOND VEHICLE, THE SHIPMENT WAS DELIVERED TO THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY.  ALL MATERIAL COLLECTED IN THE CONTAINMENT PAIL WAS ADDED TO THE SHIPMENT FOR DISPOSAL.  ONCE EMPTY, THE VEHCILE WHICH WAS EXPERIENCED THE LEAK WAS INSPECTED AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT A SMALL AMOUNT OF FOREIGN DEBRIS. (i.e. SAND AND GRIFT PARTICLES) HAD LODGED IN THE VALVE ASSEMBLY PREVENTING A COMPLETE SEAL FROM BEING ACHEIVED.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE ALL VEHICLES WILL CONTINUE TO BE ROUTINELY INSPECTED TO ENSURE THAT ALL VALVE ASSEMBLIES ARE FREE OF FOREIGN DEBRIS WHICH COULD PREVENT A PROPER SEAL FROM BEING ACHIEVED.

AGAIN, THE DRUMS WERE BLOCKED AND BRACED IN THE SAME MANNER AS PREVIOUSLY DESCRIBED.  INTERIOR INSPECTION DID VERIFY THERE HAD BEEN LEAK.  HOWEVER, UNABLE TO DETERMINE HOW MANY DRUMS WERE INVOLVED OR CAUSE AT THIS TIME.  AN EXTERIOR INSPECTION OF CONTAINER APLU 881832, WAS MADE NOTING RESIDUE OF LEAK ON THE TOP RIGHT SIDE AS WELL AS SPLATTERED ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE CONTAINER.  S/A HAZMAT LIBBY CONACTED LINDS MANZI, APL, HAZ/MAT CENTER, OAKLAND, CA/  ADVISED HER THERE WAS NO IMMEDIATE DANGER AND THAT BOTH CONTAINERS HAD BEEN ISOLATED. SHEN THEN ADVISED SHOW WOULD CONTACT AND CONTRACT WITH FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL, SEATTLE TO CLEAN THE EXTERIOR OF CONTAINER APLU 881832 AND UNLOAD, IDENTIFY AND OVERPAC THE LEAKING DRUM(S) IN CONTAINER APLU 883462 AT 0800 HOURS, 3/20/96.  PAUL SCHMIDT, FIELD SUPERVISOR, FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL, SEATTLE AND 3 MAN CREW DEVELOPED 1-30 GALON DRUM LOADED ON THE BOTTOM RIGHT SIDE TO BE SITTING ON A TIE DOWN CLEAT WELDED ON THE SIDE FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER IN QUESTIONS.  THE DRUM RIPPED ON THE CLEAT UNTIL IT PUNCTURED THE BOTTOM.  HOWEVER THE LEAK WAS KEPT TO A MINIMUM ON ACCOUNT THE CLEAT ALSO ACTED AS A PLUG.  THE 1 LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK DRUM AND RELOADED WITH THE REST OF THE DRUMS THAT HAD BEEN REMOVED, DOORS CLOSED, SEAL UP 185056 APPLIED AND RELEASED FOR DELIVERY. CONTAINER APLU 881832, WAS WIPED CLEAN AND ALSO RELEASED FOR DELIVERY,

column42: PHOSPHORUS, WHITE OR YELLOW DRY OR UNDER WATER OR IN SOLUTION
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1710 HOURS ON 3-15-96 MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS STEVE BURNS.  HE ADVISED THAT LOADED TANK CAR ACFX 94665, CONTAINING YELLOW PHOSPHORUS WAS ON FIRE EAST BOWL TRACK 49.  ON ARRIVAL AT LOCATION, MGR LERCH OBSERVED FROM A SAFE DISTANCE, A SMALL WHITE CLOUD OF SMOKE CENTERED OVER THE TOP OF THE CAR.  AFTER SEVERAL MINUTES, THE SMOKE HAD DISSIPATED INTO THE ATMOSPHERE. UPON DETERMINING IT WAS SAFE TO APPROACH, MGR LERCH INSPECTED OF THE LOADING PLATFORM.  THE MATERIAL HAD BURNED ITSELF OUT LEAVING A RUST COLORED RESIDUE.  MGR LERCH APPLIED WATER THE AFFECTED AREA OF THE CAR TO FREEZE ANY REMAINING UNBURNED PRODUCT.  THE CAR WAS THEN INSPECTED BY MECHANICAL PERSONNEL AND ISOLATED IN THE OKS, (MINI REPAIR TRACK) FOR FURTHER OBSERVATION.  CAUSE OF RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE HYDRAULIC SURGE ACTION OF PRODUCT WITHIN THE CAR, RESULTING FROM THE OVERSPEED IMPACT OF THE CAR INTO STATIONARY CAR GRPX 944251.  THIS ACTION FORCED PRODUCT OUT OF THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  ON 3-18-96 EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL FROM MONSANTO ARRIVED.  IN A JOINT EFFORT WITH MONSANTO PERSONNEL.  CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANGERS, DON LOW, FRANK LERCH ASSISTED IN THE REPLACEMENT OF THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE AND NEUTRALIZED OF RESIDUE PRODUCT ON CAR.  THE CAR WAD THEN TRIP INSPECTED AND RERELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.  THE CONTAMINATED VALVE, ALONG WITH CLEAN UP MATERIAL USED TO NEUTRALIZED THE PHOSPHOROUS, WAS PLACED INTO RESIDUE EMPTY TANK CAR, ACFX 94660 RETURNING TO MONSANTO , ID., FOR FURTHER HANDLING AND DISPOSAL OF WASTE.  THERE WERE NO WATERWAYS, GROUND EXPOSURED OR INJURIES REPORTED RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.

DURING ROUTINE INSPECTION BY MECHANICAL FORCES AT UNION PACIFIC'S RAIL YARD ATLIVIONIA, LOUISIANA, THIS TANK CAR WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING A SMALL AMOUNT  PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET NOZZLE CAP.  UPRR REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, T.M. ROBINSON WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE CAR.  ROBINSON FOUND THE CAUSE OF THE LEAKAGE TO BE FROM THE FOLLOWING:OPERATING ROD FOR THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS LOOSE, AND THE GASKET IN THE BOTTOM OUTLET NOZZLE WAS BRITTLE.  ROBINSON TIGHTENED THE OPERATING ROD AND SECURED THE PACKING GLAND.  THIS STOPPED THE CAR FROM LEAKING.  THE BRITTLE GASKET IN THE NOZZLE CAP WAS REPLACED FOR DESTINATION.  ROBINSON NOTIFIED MR. JOE BABER OF CHEMTREC FOR SHIPPER NOTIFICATION. ON THURSDAY, 3.21.96, ROBINSON TELEPHONED MR. STEVE TURCHI, OPERATIONS MANAGER FOR TAKTANK DEER PARK TERMINAL.  ROBINSON AND TURCHI DISCUSSED ALL OF THE DETAILS OF THE INCIDENT.  TURCHI ADVISED THAT HE WOULD TAKE APPROPRIATE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT A REOCCURENCE OF THIS EVENT.

column168: THE TANK CAR WAS FOUND TO BE DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET NOZZLE BY TRAINMEN AT UNION PACIFIC'S RAIL YARD AT LIVIONIA, LOUISIANA, MIKE CAMPBELL, DIRECTOR OF TERMINAL OPERATIONS WAS NOTIFIED AND THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AT LIVONIA WITHOUT INCIDENT.  CAMPBELL NOTIFIED UPRR REGIONAL MANAGER- CHEMICAL TRANSPORATAION SAFETY, T.M. ROBINSON. IN ADDITION CAMPBELL NOTIFIED THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, THE POINE COUPEE PARISH 911 CENTER, THE LOUISIANA DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY AND CHEMTREC. ROBINSON RESPONDED TO THE LEAKING CAR ANS OBSERVED A SLOW DRIP LEAK FROM THE FLANGE OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET NOZZLE AND THE TANK.  A BUCKET WAS POSITIONED TO CONTAIN THE SPILLAGE.  ROBINSON INSPECTED THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE, OPERATING STEM AND FOUND THAT THE VALVE WAS FULLY CLOSED.  ROBINSON THEN REMOVED THE PLUG FROM THE AUXILLARY VALVE ON THE BOTTOM OUTLET NOZZLE CAP AND OPENED THE VALVE.  THIS DRAINED THE ACCUMULATED LIQUID FROM THE OUTLET NOZZLE INTO THE BUCKET.  THE DRIPPING FROM BETWEEN THE OUTLET FLANGE AND TANK STOPPED.  A SLOW DRIPPING PAST THE INTERNAL VALVE REMAINED.  ROBINSON CONTACTED MR. DEAN SMITH, EMERGENCY RESPONSE COORDINATOR FOR DOW CHEMICAL AT PLAQUEMINE, LA. SMITH WAS INFORMED OF THE SITUATION AND DISPATCHED TWO TECHNICIANS FROM DOW, MR. LUCIUS BOUDREAUX AND MR. CLIFF HOOD.  BOUDREAUX AND HOOD APPLIED A TEMPORARY SEALANT AROUND THE OUTLET NOZZLE FRAME THAT WOULD PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE UNTIL THE CAR COULD BE RETURNED TO DOW'S PLANT AT PLAWUEMINE.  THE CAR WAS RETURNED TO DOW'S PLANT DURING THE EARLY MORNING OF SATURDAY, 3/16/96 WITHOUT INCIDENT.

ROQUET ARRIVED ON THE SCENE, SHE FOUND THE LEAK WAS IN THE SIDE OF A CASING THAT EXTENDED BELOW THE CAR.  THE BOTTOM VALVE WAS BELOW THE LEAK.  THE LEAK WAS UNAFFECTED WHETHER THE VALVE WAS OPEN OR CLOSED. THE CAR WAS MISSING 3 PLACARDS. THE PLACARDS WERE REPLACED AND THE CAR WAS STENCILED "LEAKY CAR DO NOT LOAD UNTIL REPAIRES". A CHECK WITH ELF ATOCHEM THROUGH CHEMTREC FOUND THE CAR REALLY CONTAINED SODIUM HYDROXIDE.  THE RUPTURE DISC WAS FOUND TO HAVE BLOWN. THIS WAS REPLACED.  BOB THEIS WITH ELF ATOCHEM IN WILLBRIDGE, OR SAID HE WOULD FOLLOW-UP THE WAYBILING ERROR.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: ON 030696 AT APPROXIMATELY 9 AM, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, GEOFFREY REEDER RECEIVED A CALL FROM MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS, DAVID BADER, THAT EXXON EMPLOYEES HAD OBSERVED A VAPOR COMING FROM THE TOP OF THIS CAR.  UPON EXAMINATION, THEY FOUND THE CAR WAS OVERLOADED, THE OUTAGE INDICATING 0" AND 260PSI.  EXXON DETERMINED THE QUICKEST WAY TO REDUCE THE LOAD WAS TO USE A FLARE TO BURN SOME OF THE EXCESS PRODUCT.  THE CAR ON THE ADJACENT TRACKS WERE REMOVED. THE FENCE BETWEEN EXXON AND RAILROAD PROPERTY WAS CUT FOR EASY ACCESS.  A PORTABLE FLARE STACK WAS ERECTED ON EXXON PROPERTY AND ABOUT 120 FEET OF 1" HOSE RUN FROM THE CAR TO THE FLARE. AFTER APPROXIMATELY 2 HOURS OF BURNING THE PRESSURE READ 113PSI AND OUTAGE AT 3 3/4".  THE PROCESS WAS HALTED.  THE CAR WAS THEN MOVED TO EXXON'S UNLOADING RACK WHERE IT WAS FULLY UNLOADED. CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED.

column168: ON 030496 AT APPROXIMATELY 2 PM, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, GEOFFREY REEDER WAS MAKING ROUTINE TANK CAR INSPECTIONS AT LLOYD YARD IN SPRING, TEXAS.  UPON OPENING THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER, REEDER HEARD THE HISS OF ESCAPING GAS.  USING LEAK DETECTING LIQUID, THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK WAS DETERMINED TO BE THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  THE PRESSURE ON THE CAR WAS 40 PSI.  SINCE THE CAR WAS A RESIDUE RETURNING HOME, REEDER DETERMINED THE O-RINGS IN THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WERE PROBABLY DEFECTIVE. CTS PERSONEL BOB STINE AND TOM ROBINSON CAME TO THE SCENE TO ASSIST IN REPLACING THE DEFECTIVE PARTS.  THE CONSIGNEE WAS NOTIFIED AND THE CAR RELEASED FOR NORMAL MOVEMENT.

A UNION PACIFIC SWITCH CREW REPORTED THE SMELL OF AMMONIA IN THE UPRR COUNCIL BLUFFS WEST YARD.  SUBSEQUENT INSPECTION BY UPRR SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS KEN DECHANT DISCLOSED THE LEAKING CAR TO BE PLMX 34525.  DECHANT REMOVED SEAL CCPRR-516841 FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING, AND NOTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE A-END LIQUID VALVE.  LIQUID WAS RUNNING UP THE STEM OF THE ANGLE VALVE, WITH ALL SPILLAGE CONTAINED WITHIN THE HOUSING.  TIGHTENING OF THE VALVE STEM PACKING NUT STOPPED THE LEAK COMPLETELY.  SPILLAGE WAS ALLOWED TO VAPORIZED AND DISSIPATE, WITH NO EVIDENCE OF CONTINUED LEAKAGE.  CHEMTREC FILE # 42422.  INCIDENT DID NOT MEET REPORTING CRITERIA OF IOWA DEPT. OF NATURAL RESOURCES.  CAR WAS RESEALED WITH UPE-277495 AND RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.

AT 0450 HOURS ON SATURDAY THE 2ND DAY OF MARCH 1996, MGR. RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED BY MR. RICH TAYLOR OF THE SALT LAKE CAR DEPARTMENT THAT CAR NATX29159 WAS OBSERVED LEAKING AND HAD BEEN SET OUT IN THE OLD CAB TRACK, FOR REPAIR.  INSPECTION REVEALED CAR IS A SINGLE SHELL CAR AND AS LEAKING FROM WELD ON THE LAST RING ON THE A-END, SLIGHTLY TO THE RIGHT OF THE BOTTOM CENTER ABOUT 12 INCHES FROM THE BOLSTER.  LEAKING AT A RATE OF APPROXIMATELY ONE CUP PER HOUR.  MGR. RODABOUGH PLACED A CONTAINER TO CATCH THE LEAKING PRODUCT AND CALLED AMOCO, TO ARRANGE FOR UNLOADING. AMOCO SENT TWO TECHNICIANS MR. KEVIN ZIEGLER AND MR CRAIG PIERCE.  WITH THE USE OF BANDING AND A RUBBER PATCHING MATERIAL WE WERE ABLE TO STOP THE LEAK. THE CAR WAS THEN MOVED TO AMOCO FOR UNLOADING PURPOSES.  CHEMTREC MR. JOE BABER, FURNISHED WITH DETAILS AND THE SHIPPER STAN TRANS ALSO ADVISED ABOUT THE INCIDENT.

PACKAGE WAS FOUND LEAKING ON THE PURPLE BELT AND FIRST RESPONDER WAS CALLED.  FIRST RESPONDER USED DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEETS AS WELL AS ALL PPE.  ALL SALVAGEABLE MATERIAL WAS REPACKED AND SENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER.  ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP.
FOLLOWED DECISION TREE, RESPONDED USING FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET WORE ALL PPE.  ABSORBED WITH SOLUSORB.  PLACED ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIAL IN PLASTIC BAG.  PROCESSED THROUGH DMP.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: AT APPROX. 1430 HRS, 3-11-96, I STOPPED AT THE PETRO TRUCKSTOP, EXIT 104 1-95 SOUTHBOUND IN RUTHER GLEN, VA. FOR FUEL.  DURING THE FUELING, WHILE CHECKING THE TIRES ON THE TRAILER, I DISCOVERED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL LEAKING FROM BOTH SIDES OF THE TRAILER REAR.  I NOTIFIED THE MANAGER (BERNIE ROOK, 804-448-2394) WHO CALLED 911 FOR THE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  RESPONSE WAS MADE BY THE BOWLING GREEN VOL. FIRE DEPARTMENT.  (1 PUMPER TRUCK - 1 FIRE CHIEF CAR - 1 AMBULANCE, 1 HAZMAT RESPONSE UNIT.)  I NOTIFIED LOU CORDI THEN RETURNED TO THE SPILL AREA.  AT THIS TIME, A UNIT ARRIVED FROM THE CAROLINE COUNTY HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM, THE CAROLINE COUNTY DEPT, THE VIRGINIA DEP, THE VIRGINIA STATE POLICE AND THE CAROLINE COUNTY SHERIFF DEPT.  LOU CORDI HAD CALLED IMS ENVIRO WHO RESPONDED APPROX. 15 MINUTES LATER.  THIS WAS APPROX. 1615 HOURS.  IML WOULD BE DOING THE CLEAN-UP AFTER THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD COMPLETED CONTAINING THE SPILL.  UPON OPENING THE TRAILER DOORS IT WAS NOTED THAT IN THE LAST ROW TOWARD THE REAR OF THE TRAILER (1) DRUM WAS LEAKING.  FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL SAID THIS WAS CAUSED BY THE DRUM RUBBING AGAINST THE DRUM NEXT TO IT?  THE LOAD LOCK I HAD PLACED ON THE REAR ROW WAS STILL IN PLACE.  AT APPROX 1730 HRS, I WAS TOLD TO MOVE TO AN ISOLATED AREA OF THE PARKING LOT TO AWAIT THE CLEANUP EQUIPMENT.  THIS ARRIVED AT 1745.  IN THE MEANTIME, I WAS CONTACTED BY PHONE BY MR. STEPHEN TURNER, VIRGINIA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIROMENTAL QUALITY (703-490-7345).  MR. TURNER ISSUED A PROVISIONAL DEQ NUMBER VAP-AP000009302 IN ORDER TO HAVE THE SPILLED MATERIAL, WHICH HAD BEEN CLEANED UP AND PUT IN DRUMS, LOADED ON THE TRUCK.  THE TRUCK WAS ALLLOWED TO PROCEED.  THE CLEAN UP AND RELEASE WAS COMPLETED AT NOTE-MANIFEST LA-A3336318 LINE "C" DOES NOT CONTAIN A COMMON NAME LINE "D" CONTAINS BENZENE & LEAD.  IN CONTACTING CC LAB, I WAS TOLD TO REPORT TO THE RESPONDING PEOPLE THE DRUM CONTAINED 30-99% XYLENE-TOLUENE AND ACETONE, AND 1-70% PAINT AND SOLVENT BASED WATER.  ALSO RESPONDING WITH (1) PUMPER TRUCK WAS THE FROG LEVEL VOL. FIRE DEPT. AND (3) CARS FROM THE VIRGINIA STATE POLICE DEPT OF MOTOR VEHICLE ENFORCEMENT.  MR. TURNER INSTRUCTED ME TO CALL AFTER (0800 - 3-12-96) TO INFORM HIM OF THE NUMBER OF DRUMS LOADED FROM THE CLEAN-UP.  HE ALSO SAID HE WOULD BE IN TOUCH WITH TOM HUNT ON 3-12-96.  LOU CORDI HAD NOTIFIED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND RECEIVED INCIDENT #330529.  2315-NOTIFIED BY IMS PERSONNEL THAT WHILE MOVING THE DRUMS FOR CLEANING INTERIOR OF TRAILER THEY FOUND (2)* DRUMS LEAKING BECAUSE OF HOLES IN THEM.  THE HOLES HAD BEEN COVERED WITH DUCT TAPE.  HAD TO STOP THE CLEANING WHILE THEY WAITED FOR MORE OVERPACKS. THEY NOTIFIED ALL AGENCIES MENTIONED ABOVE, (FIRE DEPT-STATE DEP ETC.). FIRE DEPARTMENT LEFT THE SCENE 0215, 3-12-96.  SITE COMMANDER:  ROGER RAINES, BOX 447, BOWLING GREEN, VA.  22427, 804-633-9831. TRANSPORT SOUTH INC WAS PUMPING DIESEL INTO FUEL TANK AT CONWAY SOUTHERN EXPRESS IN NASHVILLE, TN. WHEN THE CAP BLEW OFF HIS PUMP.  ABOUT 30 GALS OF FUEL POURED OUT TO THE GROUND.  THE TRANSPORT SOUTH DRIVER SHUT OFF PUMP IMMEDIATELY.  DAMED UP THE SPILLED FUEL WITH SAND THAT WE HAVE ON SITE.  HE THEN PUT SOME ENZYME ON THE DIESEL.  DAVID HIGH, TERMINAL MGR FOR TRANSPORT SOUTH, CAME TO SITE AND CLEANED UP SPILL.  DAVID PUT CONTAMINATED SAND IN WASTE DRUM AND REMOVED IT FROM CONWAY SOUTHERN'S YARD.

column168: A HAZARDOUS INCIDENT WAS BROUGHT TO MY ATTENTION AROUND 2230 ON 3/6/96. AFTER LOOKING AT THE SITUATION, I DISCOVERED 3-5 GAL PAILS HAD PUNCTURED BY FORKLIFT BLADES.  PERSON RESPONSIBLE FAILED TO SIGN HIS NAME ON LOADING MANIFEST SO NO CONCRETE FACTS CAN LEAD TO WHO ACTUALLY DID DAMAGE.  AFTER RESEARCHING FREIGHT LOADED BEHIND PAILS, THE PRO # INDICATED THAT NCV DS/R MR. ALEXANDER WAS PERSON RESPONSIBLE.  UNLOADED DAMAGED FREIGHT AND SEPARATED WHAT COULD BE DELIVERED.  DISPOSED OF 3 DAMAGED PAILS AND OIL DRY IN 85 GAL HAZ MAT SPILL CONTAINER.  BROUGHT TO VERN HARTNETT'S ATTENTION AND HE HANDLED DS/R MR. ALEXANDER.

column168: GENE WILSON LOADED A SKID BEHIND THE DRUM, THE FORKLIFT BLADE PUNCTURED THE DRUM.

WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER 415-3175, THE UNLOADING DRIVER, KEITH WOLFE, NOTICED TWO OF THE PAPER BAGS OF THE SHIPMENT LEAKING A WHITE POWDER. KEITH IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE DOOR TO THE TRAILER AND NOTIFIED TODD WALKER, SERVICE CENTER MANAGER.  AFTER CONSULTING THE SHIPPING DOCUMENTS TO IDENTIFY THE SUBSTANCE, CARLIN CALDWELL, CSE SAFETY SUPERVISOR WAS NOTIFIED.  MR. CALDWELL THEN CALLED CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER TO OBTAIN MSDS SHEETS AND PROPER HANDLING INSTRUCTIONS.  UPON RECEIVING DIRECTION FROM CHEMTREC, WE WERE ADVISED ON THE PROPER PROCEDURES FOR CONTAINING AND CLEAN-UP.  RECOMMENDATIONS:  SINCE IT APPEARS THAT THE PUNCTURED BAGS SLIPPED BETWEEN THE X BOARDS OF THE PALLET CAUSING THEM TO BE STRUCK BY THE BLADES OF THE FORKLIFT WHEN ATTEMPTING TO MOVE AT THE FAC, CARDBOARD SHOULD FIRST BE PLACED ON THE SKID BEFORE LOADING THE BAGS AND THEN BAGS SHOULD BE SECURED TO PALLET WITH SHRINK/STRETCH WRAP.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: DURING ROUTE BETWEEN TERMINAL LOCATINS. DRIVER HIT A GROUND RAIL.  THE TRAILER OVERTURNED CAUSING HEAVIER FREIGHT TO TOPPLE ON TOP OF CARTONS OF PAINT.  DUE TO THE NATURE OF THE INCIDENT, EMERGENCY TEAMS WERE CALLED TO THE SCENE.  IT WAS DETERMINED BY THE PENNSYLAVNIA DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION, PENNSYLVANIA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION, AND LOCAL HAZMAT TEAMS THAT THERE WAS NO SERIOUS THREAT TO HEALTH OR THE ENVIRONMENTAL DUE TO THE MINIMAL HAZMAT ON BOARD THE TRUCK AND THE REMOVAL OF THE VARIOUS FREIGHT FROM THE TRUCK BEGAN.  AT 11:25 AM WORK WAS HALTED DUE TO THE DISCOVERY OF AN OPEN CONTAINER OF PAINT.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT RETURNED TO THE SCENE.  INTERSTATE 80 WAS CLOSED AND WORK CONTINUED. 3 2.5 LITER CONTAINER AUTO COLOR P210-796 NR, 2 1 GALLON CONTAINER AUTO COLOR P426-PP10, 2 5 LITER CONTANER AUTO COLOR P190-0640, 1 1 GALLON CONTAINER AUTO COLOR P55-761.  THESE CONTAINERS WERE OVERPACKED.  ALL OTHER CONTAINER WERE ALSO OVERPACKED. SOIL WAS EXCAVATED AND TAKEN TO CENTRE COUNTY SOLID WASTE AUTHORITY PER THE PENNSYLAVNIA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION.  THE PAINT CONTAINERS WERE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR MITIGATION. SAME AS REPORT # 96040606 A SAME AS REPORT # 96040606 B

column168: DOCK FOREMAN, BRIAN HINES WAS WALKING PAST THE TRAILER WHEN DOCKMAN, DOUG LEE ADVISED BRIAN THAT A DRUM WAS LEAKING.  MR. LEE INDICATED THAT HE HAD DISCOVERED THE DRUM LEAKING WHEN HE WAS LOADING OTHER FREIGHT ON THE TRAILER.  DRUM APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN DAMAGED BY OTHER FREIGHT OR A FORKLIFT IN THE LOADING PROCESS.  SPILL CONTAINED AND DRUM IS BEING HELD FOR DISPOSITION.

D/S JOHN PULEO WAS ATTEMPTING TO PLACE DRUM ON A BARREL TRUCK.  WHEN HE WENT TO BREAK BACK THE DRUM, THE BOTTOM SLIPPED OFF THE LIPS OF THE BARREL TRUCK CAUSING A SMALL PUNCTURE IN THE DRUM.  D/S PULEO IMMEDIATELY LAID THE DRUM ON ITS SIDE WITH THE TOP UP.  THE SMALL RELEASE OF CORROSIVE WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH BAKING SODA.  THIS EVENT HAPPENED ON THE LOADING DOCK AT CF MOTORFREIGHT.  EMPLOYEES AT THE TERMINAL WERE GIVEN INSTRUCTIONS TO USE EXTREME CAUTION WHEN USING A BARREL TRUCK ON A DRUM TO BE SURE THAT THEY HAVE COMPLETE CONTROL BEFORE BREAKING THE DRUM BACK ONTO THE BARREL TRUCK.

SKIDS WERE PUT IN BAY 74 BY EMPLOYEE 68827 AND EMPLOYEE JOEL ROOKER WAS TOLD TO STACK OUT THAT AREA.  WHEN HE ARRIVED HE DISCOVERED THAT 2 BAGS OF PRO 452413010 HAD BEEN TORN OPEN ON THEIR SIDE.  WE RECOUPED THE ENTIRE SKID AND REMOVED THE 2 DAMAGED BAGS.  THE 2 DAMAGED BAGS WERE REMOVED AND PLACED IN OSAD AWAITING APPROVAL TO RETURN TO SHIPPER PER SHIPPER'S REQUEST.  EMPLOYEE JOEL ROOKER LATER COMPLAINED OF AN UPSET STOMACH AND WAS SENT TO BAPTIST MINOR MEDICAL.  HE WAS RELEASED AND CLEARED OF ANY PROBLEMS.
MR. APUAN WAS LOADING.  HE KNOCKED THIS OVER AND BROKE ONE BOTTLE.  MR. WESTREICHER RECOOPERED THIS AND PLACED THE DAMAGED GOODS IN RECOOP DRUM. DRUM IS IN HAZ-MAT TRAILER.

WHEN REGULAR EMPLOYEE T J RAYMOND LIFTED DOCK PLATE TO PLACE IN TRAILER, DOCK PLATE SLIPPED OFF AND BENT DOCK HOOK NICKING BOTTOM SIDE OF PLASTIC 55 GALLON DRUM.  THIS CAUSED A SMALL HAIRLINE CRACK IN DRUM.  THE DRUM WAS TURNED UP SIDE DOWN, DRIED AND CRACK WAS COVERED WITH SILVER TRAILER TAPE. THE DRUM WAS THEN UP RIGHTED AND PLACED ON PIECE OF CARDBOARD FOR OBSERVATION.  WHEN IT WAS DETERMINED THAT DRUM WAS STILL LEAKING, IT WAS PLACED INTO A PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED TO CONSIGNEE.

column168: THE ELIZABETHTOWN KT FIRE DEPATRMENT REPORTED A RAIL CAR WAS GIVING OFF A CLOUD IN A TRAIN THAT WAS PART IN A SIDING IN ELIZABETHTOWN.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT REPORTED A "BLACK LIKE" ODOR AND EVACUATED APPROXIMATELY 120 PEOPLE AS A PRECAUTION.  LOCAL AUTHORITIES COULD NOT PROVIDE A CAR NUMBER TO ASSIST CSXT IN DETERMINING THE PRODUCT INVOLVED.  CSXT HAZ MAT MGR., TL MURTA, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND KY DEPT OF ENV. CONDUCTED A SURVEY OF THE TRAIN BUT OBSERVED NO CLOUD NOR SMELLED AN ODOR.  MURTA INSPECTED THE 4 HAZ MAT CARS IN TE TRAIN AND FOUND NO EVIDENCE OF A RELEASE, HOWEVER GATX 10474, RESIDUE FLUOROSILICIC ACID HAD LOOSE BOLTS ON THE LIQUID LOADING CONNECTION.  THE RUPTURE DISK WAS OK.  THE EVACUATION WAS LIFITED AT 2400 HOURS.

column168: PACKAGE WAS UNLOADED WITH LEAKAGE NOTED ON THE BOX.  EXAMINATION OF THE INNER CONTAINER REVEALED THAT THE PLASTIC BOTTLE HAD LOOSE CAP(S) WHICH ALLOWED THE CONTENTS TO ESCAPE.  THE LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED.  THE CAP(S) WERE SECURED.  CARTON WAS WET BUT OTHERWISE UNDAMAGED.  PACKAGE WAS REPACKED FOR RETURN TO THE SHIPPER.

A LOOSE CAP CAUSED THE SPILL OF 1/2 GALLON OF CORROSIVE LIQUID (SODIUM HYDROXIDE) THROUGH THE OUTER PACKAGING AND EVENTUALLY ONTO THE LOADING DOCK.  THE SPILLED LIQUID WAS TESTED WITH PH TAPE AND FOUND TO BE PH13. THE LIQUID WAS NEUTRALIZED USING SODIUM BICARBONATE AND THE SPILL CLEANED UP USING PPE, THE DECISION TREE, AND THE CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET.  THE CAP WAS TIGHTENED AND ALL BOTTLES WERE PLACED IN A PLASTIC BAG.  THE PACKAGE WAS THEN RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.
DOCKWORKER DISCOVERED A LOOSE CAP ON ONE BOTTLE.  CAP WAS TIGHTENED AND FORWARDED ON TO DESTINATION.

I WASL CALLED INTO THE TRAILER IN UNLOAD BAY 10 AND DISCOVERED A 5 GALLON DRUM WITH A UPS 5-PART MSDS FORM MARKED RESIN SOLUTION. THE LID HAD NOT BEEN PROPERLY SECURED AND APPROXIMATELY 1 (ONE) GALLON HAD SPILLED OUT. 10 (TEN) OTHER PACKAGES HAD BEEN TAINTED. I REMOVED ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIALS AND FOLLOWING THE UPS RESPONSE GUIDE DRIED THE CONTAMINENTS WITH SOLUSORB. I ALSO DRIED THE SPILLAGE IN THE TRAILER IN THE SAME MANNER. ALL CONTAMINATED ITEMS INCLUDING THE DRUM WERE PLACED IN A DMP GIVEN TEMPORARY ID# 3-14-02P AND INFORMATION WAS SENT OF THE MALLINCRODT FOR DISPOSAL INFORMATION.
